The computation of the given integral involves several steps.

\textbf{Step 1.} In the first step we apply the substitution rule with
$u = \ln(x)$. This implies $du/dx = 1/x$ and in particular $dx = x du$.
Hence,

\begin{align*}\int \cos(\ln(x)) \, dx = \int \cos(u)\cdot x \, du\end{align*}

We have to rewrite $x$ in terms of $u$. This can be done by
exponentiating the substitution equation\begin{align*}e^u = x.\end{align*} We arrive at

\begin{align*}\int \cos(u)\cdot x \, du = \int \cos(u)e^u \, du\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 2.} We apply integration by parts with $f(u) = \cos(u)$ and
$g'(u) = e^u$:

\begin{align*}\int \cos(u)e^u \, du = \cos(u)e^u + \int \sin(u)e^u \, du\end{align*}

Integration by parts onto the integral in the right-hand side with
$f(u)=\sin(u)$ and $g'(u)=e^u$ yields

\begin{align*}\int \sin(u)e^u \, du = \sin(u)e^u - \int \cos(u)e^u \, du\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 3.} Step 1 and Step 2 together results in the equation

\begin{align*}
\int \cos(u)e^u \, du &= \cos(u)e^u + \int \sin(u)e^u \, du \\
&= \cos(u)e^u + \sin(u)e^u - \int \cos(u)e^u \, du\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 4.} We bring the integral on the right-hand side of the
equation over to the left-hand side:

\begin{align*}2\int\cos(u)e^u \, du =  \cos(u)e^u + \sin(u)e^u = e^u(\sin(u) + \cos(u))\end{align*}

Finally, we divide the equation by 2:

\begin{align*}\int\cos(u)e^u \, du = \frac{e^u}{2}(\sin(u) + \cos(u)) + C\end{align*}

where $C$ is an arbitrary constant

\textbf{Step 5.} The last step is to rewrite our results in terms of
$x$. Remember, that our very first step was the substitution
$u = \ln(x)$. Therefore

\begin{align*}
\int \cos(\ln(x)) \, dx &= \int \cos(u)e^u \, du \\
 &= \frac{e^u}{2}(\sin(u) + \cos(u)) + C \\
&= \frac{x}{2}(\sin(\ln(x)) + \cos(\ln(x))) + C\end{align*}

where we used $e^u = x$.
